=0Ashareholders, who would have sold to him at $50 (or $54.20), not $39, if=
 he had =0Adisclosed his trading.=0A=0AThere is some reason to think that M=
usk, or at least his advisers, were trying =0Ato keep his purchases secret =
to avoid driving up the price, and that they =0Aweren=E2=80=99t particularl=
y concerned about complying with the rules. TheSEC=E2=80=99s =0Acomplaint s=
ays <>:=0A=0AMusk understood that any substantial increase in Twitter=E2=80=
=99s common stock price =0Awould increase his costs to purchase shares. Acc=
ordingly, Musk=E2=80=99s wealth manager =0Acautioned the broker to make the=
 purchases in a way that would minimize any =0Aincrease in Twitter=E2=80=99=
s stock price that might result from the purchases. ...=0A=0AIn or around l=
ate February 2022, the broker repeatedly suggested to Musk=E2=80=99s =0Awea=
lth manager that Musk obtain legal advice as to his obligations under the =
=0Afederal securities laws to publicly disclose his holdings if he became t=
he =0Abeneficial owner of at least five percent of Twitter=E2=80=99s outsta=
nding common stock.=0A=0ANeither Musk nor his wealth manager sought or obta=
ined legal advice in =0AFebruary or March 2022 as to Musk=E2=80=99s obligat=
ions under the federal securities =0Alaws to publicly disclose his Twitter =
holdings.=0A=0AOn or about February 28, 2022, the broker asked Musk=E2=80=
=99s wealth manager whether =0AMusk wanted to continue buying shares of Twi=
tter common stock up to and past =0Athe five percent beneficial ownership t=
hreshold. Musk=E2=80=99s wealth manager did not =0Aprovide an answer until =
on or about March 8, 2022.=0A=0AAt Musk=E2=80=99s direction, on or about Ma=
rch 8, 2022, Musk=E2=80=99s wealth manager =0Ainstructed the broker to cont=
inue buying shares of Twitter common stock for =0AMusk past the five percen=
t threshold.=0A=0AAnd there is an earlier, more detailed and funnier invest=
or lawsuit against =0AMusk <>, quoting correspondence between Musk=E2=80=99=
s coverage banker at Morgan =0AStanley and his wealth adviser, Jared Bircha=
ll. Morgan Stanley bought the stock =0Afor Musk but, as it kept telling Mus=
k=E2=80=99s people, it was not responsible for his =0Asecurities filings an=
d compliance. Musk=E2=80=99s lack of disclosure seems to have made =0Athe b=
anker nervous, though not that nervous. Before Musk hit 5%, he sent =0ABirc=
hall a message saying that the Twitter trade =E2=80=9Cis very closed holed =
still =0Aand will remain so. No one knows what is going on and why but you =
and me. Not =0Acompliance not anyone.=E2=80=9D (=E2=80=9CBirchall responded=
 approvingly with a =E2=80=98thumbs up=E2=80=99 =0Aemoji.=E2=80=9D) And:=0A=
=0A[Musk=E2=80=99s Morgan Stanley banker] relayed to Defendant Birchall a c=
onversation =0Awith =E2=80=A6 a Managing Director at Morgan Stanley who =E2=
=80=9Coversees the trader =0Ahandling.=E2=80=9D [The other MD] had asked [t=
he banker] whether Defendant Musk is =0A=E2=80=9Cgoing to be an activist in=
vestor=E2=80=9D because =E2=80=9Csometimes we need to know as a =0Afirm.=E2=
=80=9D To maintain the secrecy of Defendants=E2=80=99 trading strategy, [th=
e banker] =0Aabruptly shut [the other MD] down, saying =E2=80=9CYou don=E2=
=80=99t need to know,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Cno one =0Aneeds to know,=E2=80=9D a=
nd =E2=80=9Cthis convo [conversation] goes nowhere.=E2=80=9D =0A=0ABut a li=
ttle nervous: The Morgan Stanley banker did repeatedly ask Musk=E2=80=99s =
=0Aadvisers to consult a lawyer about the disclosure issues, and allegedly =
Musk=E2=80=99s =0Aadvisers kept telling him that they had and everything wa=
s fine.=0A=0AThey hadn=E2=80=99t, the rule is quite straightforward, and al=
legedly they were just =0Aignoring it to save money. [6]  <>=0A=0ATo be fai=
r, though, Elon Musk ended up spending something like $44 billion to =0Abuy=
 all of Twitter, so the $150 million or so that he saved here was pretty =
=0Amuch a rounding error, 0.34% of the deal price, barely more thanWachtell=
 =0ALipton=E2=80=99s fee <>. Bloomberg tells me that his current net worth =
is $427 billion, =0Aand it went up by $33.5 billionone Thursday last Octobe=
r <>. The $150 million =0Ajust doesn=E2=80=99t seem that material to him.=
=0A=0APresumably it was material to some of the shareholders who sold, thou=
gh. [7]  =0A<> Also: You are just supposed to follow the law! That is the p=
oint of the law! =0AYou can=E2=80=99t be like =E2=80=9Cehh I am too rich to=
 care about this.=E2=80=9D ButBloomberg News =0Areports <>:=0A=0AAlex Spiro=
, a lawyer for Musk, said the action is =E2=80=9Can admission=E2=80=9D that=
 the SEC =0Acannot bring an =E2=80=9Cactual case,=E2=80=9D because Musk =E2=
=80=9Chas done nothing wrong and =0Aeveryone sees this sham for what it is.=
=E2=80=9D=0A=0A=E2=80=9CAs the SEC retreats and leaves office, the SEC=E2=
=80=99s multi-year campaign of =0Aharassment against Mr. Musk culminated in=
 the filing of a single-count ticky =0Atak complaint against Mr. Musk under=
 Section 13(d) for an alleged =0Aadministrative failure to file a single fo=
rm =E2=80=94 an offense that, even if proven, =0Acarries a nominal penalty,=
=E2=80=9D Spiro said in a statement.=0A=0AIt=E2=80=99s an incredible statem=
ent from his lawyer, essentially asserting that Elon =0AMusk is too rich to=
 bother with the law. The SEC is asking a court to order =0AMusk to disgorg=
e about $150 million of money that he made illicitly from his =0Asecurities=
 law violations, and the lawyer=E2=80=99s response is to say that the numbe=
rs =0Ainvolved are small. (=E2=80=9CA nominal penalty,=E2=80=9D he says, an=
d in factrecent similar =0Acases <> seem to involve five- or six-digit, not=
 nine-digit, penalties.) It=E2=80=99s =0Atrue! Even if the SEC wins this ca=
se =E2=80=94 and it should; I have never seen any =0Aargument that Muskdidn=
=E2=80=99t break the rules here, and =E2=80=9CSection 13(d) imposes a =0Ast=
rict liability standard <>=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 it won=E2=80=99t get an amoun=
t of money that matters =0Avery much to Elon Musk. Still! You=E2=80=99re su=
pposed to follow the law!=0A=0AOr not, I don=E2=80=99t know. A month ago, I=
 wrote that <> =E2=80=9CElon Musk is, like, 60% =0Asubject to the law,=E2=
=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cin roughly a month, he will be, like, 20% subject to =
=0Athe law=3F=E2=80=9D We=E2=80=99ll find out I guess. You can see why the =
SEC had to get this case =0Ain before next week.=0A=0A=0AMetaverse real est=
ate=0A=0AThe Real Deal asks a very good question <>:=0A=0ARemember the Meta=
verse=3F=0A=0ABarely=3F I feel like a lot has happened since =E2=80=9Cthe m=
etaverse=E2=80=9D was a thing. But =0Athe Real Deal is a real estate public=
ation and I had almost forgotten, and was =0Apleased to be reminded, that m=
etaversereal estate was, briefly, a thing. The =0AReal Deal article is abou=
t how it isn=E2=80=99t anymore:=0A=0ASearch the word =E2=80=9Cmetaverse=E2=
=80=9D in The Real Deal=E2=80=99s archive, and you=E2=80=99ll find no =0Ash=
ortage of hyped-up headlines: A Miami brokerage peddling virtual mansions; =
a =0ACanadian investor launching the first metaverse REIT; a management com=
pany =0Ahosting the famous New Year=E2=80=99s Eve ball drop in a virtual re=
plica of a Times =0ASquare building. =E2=80=A6=0A=0ANo one is talking about=
 shelling out big bucks for a home in the metaverse in =0Athe real estate c=
hatter anymore. Instead, they=E2=80=99re writing off their losses.=0A=0AJus=
t a few months ago, the parent company of residential brokerage eXp Realty =
=0Adiscontinued its metaverse arm, known as Virbela, and in November, sold =
it back =0Ato its founders, Alex Howland and Erik Hill, in exchange for a m=
easly $252,100 =0A=E2=80=94 the cost of their canceled severance payments, =
according to a filing with the =0ASecurities and Exchange Commission.=0A=0A=
=E2=80=9CThe metaverse arm=E2=80=9D of a residential brokerage! I cannot st=
op laughing. =0AImagine buying your next apartment in the metaverse! How wo=
uld you use the =0Abathroom=3F=0A=0A=0AThings happen=0A=0AJPMorgan <> Trade=
rs Notch Record Fourth Quarter on Volatility. Goldman <> =0AProfit Doubles =
as Stock Traders Score Record Haul.Citi <> Rolls Back Key Target =0AHalfway=
 Through Fraser=E2=80=99s Revamp.BlackRock <> CEO Calls Record Client Cash =
=E2=80=98Just =0Athe Beginning=E2=80=99. Investors pour billions into S&Peq=
ual weight fund <> as tech =0Afears rise. Battery maker=E2=80=99s $5bn debt=
 deal hands Brookfieldhuge dividend <>. =0AAccess to YourAirport Lounge <> =
Is Getting Even Harder. Startup Raises $200 =0AMillion to Bring Back theWoo=
lly Mammoth <>.=0A=0AIf you'd like to get Money Stuff in handy email form, =
right in your inbox, =0Apleasesubscribe at this link <>. Or you can subscri=
