=0A=0A[1] Patrick McKenzie imagines a banker <> describing the deposit fran=
chise: =0A=E2=80=9CSome people in our local community have money and want b=
anking services. We =0Awant the right to use their money and will bank the =
heck out of them to get it. =0AWe rolled up our sleeves. We negotiated high=
-quality curb cuts with responsible =0Atransportation engineers. We leased =
up branch locations at the best =0Aintersections. We hired salesmen and tau=
ght them to wear suits. We gave away =0Afree coffee. We invited the general=
 public to come in. We opened checking =0Aaccounts for almost anyone who as=
ked. =E2=80=A6 We sponsored the Little League team. We =0Asend somebody out=
 to the middle school twice a year to give a lecture. And why=3F =0ABecause=
 our loans business needs a low-cost stable funding source. And so we =0Awe=
nt out and built it, by the sweat of our brow. We built it with bricks and =
=0Acontracts and ATMs and math and smiles. And, by God, it is now a real th=
ing. It =0Ais now part of the social and economic fabric of this town. It i=
s as real as =0Athe town itself is real.=E2=80=9D=0A=0A[2] We have talked a=
bout these accounts a couple of times before. =E2=80=9CIf you want =0Aperfo=
rmance from your savings, you need performance savings, otherwise you just =
=0Aget savings,=E2=80=9D as I once put it <>.  And <>: =E2=80=9CIf you forg=
ot to ask for =0A=E2=80=9CPerformance,=E2=80=9D you didn=E2=80=99t get it.=
=E2=80=9D=0A=0A[3] Also sort of wild: The CFPB argues that =E2=80=9CCapital=
 One represented that 360 =0ASavings was and would be the Bank=E2=80=99s on=
ly high interest savings product of its =0Akind.=E2=80=9D It never said tha=
t at all=3F =E2=80=9CIn its marketing materials, Capital One =0Areferred to=
 360 Savings as =E2=80=98360 Savings: the online savings account from =0ACa=
pital One 360=E2=80=99 and =E2=80=98The 360 Savings Account,=E2=80=99=E2=80=
=9D back when those things were =0Atrue. But, says the CFPB, =E2=80=9Cthese=
 representations gave the net impression that =0Athe 360 Savings product wa=
s *and would be* Capital One=E2=80=99s only=E2=80=9D high-yield =0Asavings =
account (emphasis added), and =E2=80=9CCapital One did not adequately discl=
ose =0Ato 360 Savings accountholders that 360 Savings would no longer be it=
s only high =0Ainterest savings account.=E2=80=9D What=3F Why=3F Capital On=
e accurately said that 360 =0ASavings was its high-yield savings product, w=
hen it was. When it wasn=E2=80=99t, it =0Astopped saying that.=0A=0A[4] Sin=
ce then, the rules have been amended <>, and now the deadline is five =0Abu=
siness days <> rather than 10 calendar days.=0A=0A[5] Actually I think the =
right number is more like $200 million. My math at =0Athe time was roughly =
=E2=80=9Che bought 13 million shares after the deadline, at about =0A$39 ea=
ch, and the stock went to about $50 after he filed, so he saved $11 per =0A=
share on 13 million shares.=E2=80=9D But realistically, once he had filed h=
is 13D, he =0Awould have *stopped* buying stock in the open market, as in f=
act he actually =0Adid. So he just wouldn=E2=80=99t have bought those 13 mi=
llion shares until the merger =0Aclosed, at which point he would have paid =
$54.20. So he saved about $15 per =0Ashare on 13 million shares.=0A=0A[6] T=
here is one nuance in the rule =E2=80=94 SEC Rule 13d-1 <> =E2=80=94 that m=
ight have =0Aconfused the Morgan Stanley banker and Musk=E2=80=99s advisers=
. At one point the banker =0Aasked Musk=E2=80=99s team if they were =E2=80=
=9Cfine with the year-end filing,=E2=80=9D suggesting that =0Ahe was confus=
ed about the deadline. If you have activist intent, as Musk =0A*obviously* =
did =E2=80=94 he was talking to the board about taking over the company! =
=E2=80=94 =0Athen you have to file a Schedule 13D within 10 calendar days d=
ays (now five =0Abusiness days) of crossing 5%. Musk decided not to do that=
. If you do *not* =0Ahave activist intent, though, you can file a Schedule=
 13G, which is what Musk =0Aoriginally did. The Schedule 13G deadline is mo=
re complicated: At the time of =0AMusk=E2=80=99s actions,the deadline was <=
> *either* 10 days after crossing 5%, *or* 45 =0Adays after the end of the =
*year* in which you crossed 5%. (Now the rule is five =0Abusiness days or 4=
5 days after the end of the quarter.) The difference is which =0Abox you ch=
eck on the 13G. If you checked the Rule 13d-1(b) box, saying that you =0Aar=
e an institutional investor acquiring the securities in the ordinary course=
 =0Aof business with no control intent, you get to file after year-end. If =
you =0Acheck the Rule 13d-1(c) box, saying that you are not a qualified ins=
titutional =0Ainvestor but have no =E2=80=9Cpurpose =E2=80=A6 of changing o=
r influencing the control of the =0Aissuer,=E2=80=9D then you had to file w=
ithin 10 days of crossing 5%. Musk was not an =0Ainstitutional investor, di=
d not meet the requirements of Rule 13d-1(b), and =0Aactually did correctly=
check the 13d-1(c) box <>, so his 13G was due within 10 =0Adays; the idea o=
f being =E2=80=9Cfine with the year-end filing=E2=80=9D was just wrong. =0A=
Needless to say this is not legal advice, and it is boring and complicated,=
 but =0Athe point is that Musk probably should have gotten legal advice.=0A=
=0A[7] I am not in general  super sympathetic to this complaint <>: They so=
ld =0Avoluntarily, having the same information as Musk, *except* that they =
didn=E2=80=99t =0Aknow his intentions. I generally tend to think =E2=80=9Cy=
our intentions are your =0Abusiness, and nobody should expect you to tell t=
hem your intentions before =0Atrading with you.=E2=80=9D But here there rea=
lly is a longstanding, well-known rule =0Asaying he had to disclose. His in=
tentions were, legally, everybody's business.=0A=0A=0A <> =0A=0AFollow Us  =
