</a></p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The CFPB also points out that Capital=
 One adjusted the 360 Savings rate=C2=A0<em>down=C2=A0</em>due to =E2=80=9C=
market conditions=E2=80=9D when the Fed=C2=A0<em>cut=C2=A0</em>rates, so =
=E2=80=9Cit was reasonable for consumers to=C2=A0interpret those representa=
tions to mean that the 360 Savings rate would increase when interest rates =
rose more generally.=E2=80=9D Ha! =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99ll lower your rate as=
 rates go down, but we won=E2=80=99t raise it as rates go up=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=
is pretty much standard banking.</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And:</p> =
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It was reasonable for 360 Savings =
accountholders to interpret Capital One=E2=80=99s representations that 360 =
Savings was a =E2=80=9Chigh interest=E2=80=9D account with a =E2=80=9Cbette=
r everyday interest rate,=E2=80=9D a =E2=80=9Cgreat everyday rate,=E2=80=9D=
 a =E2=80=9Ctop savings rate,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Cone of the nation=E2=80=99s=
 highest savings rates=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cone of the nation=E2=80=99s be=
st savings rates,=E2=80=9D and that 360 Savings would earn =E2=80=9Cmuch mo=
re=E2=80=9D in interest =E2=80=9Cthan . . . an average savings or money mar=
ket account,=E2=80=9D to mean they would not have to closely monitor their =
accounts=E2=80=99 interest rate because they could rely on Capital One to d=
eliver on its promises.</p></blockquote> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">No, m=
an, come on. =E2=80=9CYou don=E2=80=99t have to closely monitor your accoun=
t=E2=80=99s interest rate because you can rely on your bank to raise it whe=
never rates go up=E2=80=9D is just the opposite of banking.</p> <p style=3D=
"margin: 16px 0;">To be fair Capital One did allegedly go out of its way no=
t to tell depositors that, if they uttered the right incantations, it would=
 pay them more. Again, that=E2=80=99s the whole point, but it looks bad whe=
n you say it like this:</p> <blockquote> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The B=
ank told front-line =E2=80=9Cambassadors=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94associates who wo=
rk in the Bank=E2=80=99s physical branches=E2=80=94they =E2=80=9Cmust not p=
roactively mention the ability to convert [360 Savings accounts to 360 Perf=
ormance Savings accounts] to customers.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Similarly, the Bank f=
orbade its ambassadors from forwarding 360 Savings accountholders to Bank V=
oice=E2=80=94the Bank=E2=80=99s unit that handles account conversions=E2=80=
=94unless the accountholders =E2=80=9Cask[ed] directly about=C2=A0the abili=
ty to convert accounts.=E2=80=9D</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Likewise,=
 the Bank instructed its employees to =E2=80=9Conly be reactive in mentioni=
ng 360 Performance Savings to . . . 360 Savings account holders.=E2=80=9D=
=C2=A0It further told its employees that they could =E2=80=9C[o]nly offer t=
he option to convert [a 360 Savings] account=E2=80=9D to a 360 Performance =
Savings account in four scenarios, each of which involved a 360 Savings acc=
ountholder who was (1) already aware that 360 Performance Savings was a dis=
tinct product from 360 Savings or (2) was expressly unhappy about their 360=
 Savings interest rate.</p> </blockquote> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I gu=
ess part of the point here might be that this is why the CFPB exists. The C=
FPB is, as the name suggests, a=C2=A0<em>consumer=C2=A0</em>financial prote=
ction regulator. If consumers are unprotected financially, the CFPB steps i=
n to protect them. I have been cheerfully and whole-heartedly endorsing Cap=
ital One=E2=80=99s conduct here, but that is partly a bit, and I sympathize=
 a little with the CFPB=E2=80=99s sense that this feels shady. The <em>righ=
t </em>way to build an enduring deposit franchise is by forging mutually be=
neficial relationships of trust with customers, not by hiding the higher-yi=
elding deposit accounts on the website.</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bu=
t it=E2=80=99s hard to imagine a=C2=A0<em>bank regulator</em>, like the Fed=
, bringing a case like this.=C2=A0You suggest this case to the Fed and they=
 will say things like =E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t understand, of course the de=
posit beta is lower than 1, what is the problem.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9COnly be =
reactive in offering a higher rate to depositors who aren=E2=80=99t complai=
ning about their lower rate=E2=80=9D is Banking 101. Going out and proactiv=
ely calling depositors in low-rate accounts to switch them into higher-rate=
 accounts is not just expensive for the bank; it is potentially=C2=A0<em>de=
stabilizing</em>. Losing the cheap deposits =E2=80=94=C2=A0by telling the d=
epositors that they=E2=80=99re cheap =E2=80=94 is how banks=C2=A0<em>fail</=
em>. The Fed doesn=E2=80=99t want that.</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bu=
t this is a common tension in bank regulation: In many contexts, bank regul=
ators want banks to make a lot of money, even at the expense of customers, =
because making a lot of money is a bank=E2=80=99s main defense against dest=
abilizing failure. And so you just set up another, independent regulator, o=
ne who doesn=E2=80=99t care all that much about bank stability, to go after=
 the banks when they make too much money at the expense of their customers.=
